body.p:
You can change the icons that appear in a WebHelp Classic table of contents by assigning new
      image files in a custom CSS file. By default, these icons are defined with the following CSS
      codes (the first example is the icon that appears for a collapsed menu and the second for an
      expanded
      menu):.hasSubMenuClosed{
    background: url('../img/book_closed16.png') no-repeat;
    padding-left: 16px;
    cursor: pointer;
}.hasSubMenuOpened{
    background: url('../img/book_opened16.png') no-repeat;
    padding-left: 16px;
    cursor: pointer;
}

section.p:
To assign other icons and use a transformation scenario from within Oxygen XML
          Editor/Author, follow this procedure:

Create a custom CSS file that assigns your desired icons to the
              .hasSubMenuClosed and .hasSubMenuOpened
            properties..hasSubMenuClosed{
    background: url('TOC-my-closed-button.png') no-repeat;
}.hasSubMenuOpened{
    background: url('TOC-my-opened-button.png') no-repeat;
}

It is recommended that you store the image files in the same directory as the default
            icons (\frameworks\docbook\xsl\com.oxygenxml.webhelp.classic\oxygen-webhelp\resources\img\).

 Set the
              html.stylesheet parameter to the path of your custom CSS file.

Run the WebHelp transformation scenario to generate the output.

To assign other icons and use a script
          outside of Oxygen XML Editor/Author, follow this procedure:

Create a custom CSS file that assigns your desired icons to the
              .hasSubMenuClosed and .hasSubMenuOpened
            properties..hasSubMenuClosed{
    background: url('TOC-my-closed-button.png') no-repeat;
}.hasSubMenuOpened{
    background: url('TOC-my-opened-button.png') no-repeat;
}

It is recommended that you store the image files in the same directory as the default
            icons ([DocBook XSL
              directory]\com.oxygenxml.webhelp.classic\oxygen-webhelp\resources\img\).

Reference your custom CSS file. Use the html.stylesheet parameter in
            your transformation script and set its value to the path of your custom CSS file.



Execute the transformation script.
